<br>
You gotta remember that Japan is a country will LOTS of mountains, and a history of restricting movement between areas. This is a perfect recipe for dialects to form. I have heard that some one who speaks tohoku-ben (from northern Japan) can't under stand someone in Kyuushuu (southern Japan) if they both speak in dialect. That's why they teach Standard Japanese in the schools.<br>
<br>
Dialects can change not only the words and intonation, but the grammar as well. <br>
<br>
Examples: <br>
In tokuku-ben &quot;chi&quot;, &quot;ji&quot; and &quot;tsu&quot; get changed into &quot;zu&quot;. mochi becomes &quot;motzu&quot;. <br>
In Kansai-ben &quot;arigatou&quot; is &quot;okini&quot;.<br>
Kansai-ben also has an alternative grammar for making a noun negative. Instead of &quot;tabenai (don't eat) they would say &quot;tabehen&quot;.<br>
<br>
The list goes on and on and on. When you are learning, it is important to know what is Standard Japanese and what is the local dialect.<br>
<br>
Best,<br>
